**1) **Are you already "*using Templar's Gauntlet / SparseLoCo for pseudo gradient validation*"? Or not yet?

**2)** If you're already "*using Templar's Gauntlet / SparseLoCo for pseudo gradient validation*," did it contribute to achieving such a low LOSS in training the 1.1B model?

Thanks in advance, Karim.

The Gauntlet changes where focused solely on the incentive side of things, naturally that has some benifits in helping align miners to better reduce loss but it definetly wasn't the only contributing factor. I believe this can be proven by the fact that we implemented Gauntlet in `v1.1.8` but weren't able to converge and get these results until `v1.1.12`.

These are just some of the many changes that where made in between those two versions:
> - Using input tokens as labels since this is already done by default in HF's LlamaForCausalLM's forward loop
> - Reducing local_batch_size_train_effective from 2048 to 512
> - Increasing the outer optimiser learning rate to 1.0 to match the scaling laws of  https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.09799
> - Removing hivemind's int8 pseudo gradient compression which we believe to be hindering convergence since it has no residual tracking / feedback
All of them will have had much more impact on our ability to converge.

# SN38 – Distributed Training – Weekly Update
## 📈 Run 8 Status
This week Run 8 continued to consistnely reduce the global model's loss and improve its perfromance against lm-eval benchmarks at impressive speeds. Results to date give us some interesting insights into the benifits and drawbacks of using the Muon Optimizer whilst increasing the minimum threshold for peers joining an AllReduce from 32 to 64. We can see that whilst Wall Clock Time (the amount of time spent training) needed to reach lower global losses is shorter for Run 8 vs Run 7 the Token Budget is higher. In short, this means we need less time but more data to reach lowers losses. 
We can also see that large variances in the number of peers sometimes causes issues in training stability. Our working theory for this is that large changes in the number of peers cause large variances in batch size which then has downstream impacts on the quality of training. This gives us great insight to learn from as we look to expand the number of peers joining AllReduces in the future.
## 🚀 Global Model Upgrade
Our priority this week has been to upgrade our codebase to support multi-gpu training which is the main technical milestone needed to upgrade to a larger model size. Good progress has been made on this front (PR Link: https://github.com/dstrbtd/DistributedTraining/pull/78) where we now have a functioning miner script that can Train and AllReduce on multiple GPUs and is 80% ready for deployment.
## ⏩ Priorities for Next Week
Next week, our focus will be on cleaning up the mult-gpu miner scripts and implementing the changes on the validation side necessary for multi-gpu validation. Once completed we'll look to share this with our wider mining community to stress test the PR in prepartion for a release into main.
In the interim, we'll also look to launch Run 9 which will experiment with using quantization during the AllReduce process, another feature that will help prepare us for training a larger model size.

This week we spent some time addressing the validator issues that arose following the launch of CR4. We conducted our first 48 hour continuous run which went well but mid-way through we started observing GPU and CPU OOM issues on some of the test miners. We've identified this to be related to memory leaks that occur during FSDP state re-loading and are hoping to have a fix implemented for this early next week.
## ⏩ Priorities for Next Week
Next week, our focus will be on fixing the OOM miner issues identified during testing and moving on to finalising the validator script before starting our final round of community wide testing. We will also launch Run 9 (our final run before upgrading to an 8b size model) which will experiment with using quantization during the AllReduce process to reduce bandwidth and latency loads during model state averaging.
